00:43:33.679 --> 00:43:44.000
which is the intercept. That's, again, we're assuming it's from a population where all the

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:48.879
players from that population are more or less the same and will have more or less the same speed.

00:43:49.600 --> 00:43:57.199
We can plot the results of the model, sort of the player effects. And again,

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:05.360
this is just to take into account the fact that the players will have a max speed effect

00:44:06.879 --> 00:44:12.479
that is based on the fact that they're running across different surfaces.

00:44:13.280 --> 00:44:16.879
And that's another advantage of it. And I realize I'm not explaining this well.

00:44:17.360 --> 00:44:25.360
The each player will have an effect that is based upon how they've done across different surfaces.

00:44:25.360 --> 00:44:32.399
But this modeling technique takes into account each surface. So perhaps it's really hard to run

00:44:32.399 --> 00:44:43.199
fast on grass. Players that run fast on grass will have an adjustment to their coefficient.

00:44:43.199 --> 00:44:50.000
It's kind of like any other model where each sort of variable will take each other into account

00:44:50.000 --> 00:45:01.439
in order to have a value that makes sense. So what we get based on taking into account the surface,

00:45:02.159 --> 00:45:10.080
figuring out what the effect or the intercept will be for each NFL ID in terms of figuring

00:45:10.080 --> 00:45:16.560
out what their max speed will be, we have player effects that can kind of be thought of as

00:45:17.360 --> 00:45:23.199
plus or minus what you might expect compared to the average player on the average surface.

00:45:23.840 --> 00:45:35.520
So the thought is Matt Cole will typically be about 1.7 yards per second faster than the average

00:45:35.520 --> 00:45:43.280
kickoff coverage player on the average surface. This is the top 25 of all the players in this

00:45:43.280 --> 00:45:48.800
effect. So Y axis is player name. X axis is that plus or minus player effect. And we have the top

00:45:48.800 --> 00:45:57.360
25 in this metric. So Matt Cole is the fastest. Devin Duvernay is the slowest of the top 25,

00:45:57.360 --> 00:46:03.439
but he's still in the top 25. So this is just a way for us to take into account surface and

00:46:04.080 --> 00:46:09.439
really measure how well we expect these players to do compared to the average player.

00:46:12.080 --> 00:46:19.600
This is what the entire population looks like of these player effects. So it's a

00:46:20.479 --> 00:46:29.840
left skewed distribution with mean zero, standard deviation around one, and

00:46:32.399 --> 00:46:40.879
maybe actually more like around 0.5. And the distribution will give us information on

00:46:43.600 --> 00:46:47.520
what this looks like. And you can see that the difference between the best player and the worst

00:46:47.520 --> 00:46:53.679
player isn't necessarily that large. It's about two yards per second. The last thing that I'm

00:46:53.679 --> 00:46:59.439
going to sort of touch with this part of the presentation is one thing that I would highly

00:46:59.439 --> 00:47:04.159
suggest people do if they're planning on participating in the Big Data Bowl is to

00:47:04.159 --> 00:47:12.159
analyze a model stability to make sure that, okay, if this model predicts well for the first season,

00:47:12.159 --> 00:47:16.239
how well will it do in the second season? Or if this model predicts well for the beginning of

00:47:16.239 --> 00:47:21.679
the season, how well will it do for the end of the season? It's a way to make sure that

00:47:21.679 --> 00:47:28.239
your results are making sense and are picking up on something. So one thing that we can do here is

00:47:28.239 --> 00:47:34.879
we can do the exact same process before to get the player effects, but do one model that is only

00:47:34.879 --> 00:47:42.479
weeks one to eight, do another model that is only weeks nine to seventeen, and again we have

00:47:42.479 --> 00:47:47.679
the NFLID, the display name, and their effect. NFLID, display name, and effect. So we have two

00:47:47.679 --> 00:47:58.239
different models only using subsets of the data, and we can merge them together and compare them

00:47:58.239 --> 00:48:06.800
using a sort of an xy plot. This red line is y equals one, so if everything perfectly goes

00:48:06.800 --> 00:48:14.159
through that line, then that means we have a perfect fit. If everything, if anything is a

00:48:14.159 --> 00:48:24.800
little bit off, then we're not getting a perfect fit. Based on the fact that

00:48:25.439 --> 00:48:29.120
we sort of see obviously tree flowers here at the bottom seems a little bit off,

00:48:29.679 --> 00:48:34.399
basically since we're seeing a pretty good fit line, we feel pretty confident.

00:48:35.360 --> 00:48:40.879
And then we can do the, we can remove the outliers, we feel a little bit better.

00:48:41.919 --> 00:48:50.399
Yeah, so then we can look at the r-squared, but yeah, this is just two things that I would say to

00:48:50.399 --> 00:48:55.840
take away from this part is just one, really analyzing stability is a good way to make sure

